To use a YubiKey for passwordless sudo on Linux, you can configure pam to use the security key: 

    Install dependencies:
        (debian) sudo apt install libpam-u2f -y 
        (arch) sudo pacman -S pam-u2f
    Set up the security key for pam:
        mkdir ~/.config/Yubico
        pamu2fcfg > ~/.config/Yubico/u2f_keys 
    Configure pam:
        sudo vim /etc/pam.d/sudo, then add before the other entries:
           auth sufficient pam_u2f.so cue [cue_prompt=Tap YubiKey] 
    Test it:
        Open another terminal window, and try a sudo command
        Tap the YubiKey 

You can also use the YubiKey to: 

    Protect local authentication
    Set up the YubiKey for GDM (the desktop login screen)
    Set up Yubikey to be required for TTY login
    Secure SSH with the YubiKey 

The Yubico Pluggable Authentication Module (PAM) extends YubiKey two-factor authentication to existing Linux/Unix user authentication infrastructure. 

